<HEADLINE>
<P>
HE MASTERED THE GAME WITHOUT WINNING MASTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Commentator Byron Nelson's remarks that a golfer couldn't be judged great 
unless he has won a Masters title are rather snobbish and untrue. 
</P>
<P>
I think the British Open, which is not on the same course every year and is 
especially tough for Americans, is an even greater test. Lee Trevino won 
back-to-back British Opens in 1971 and '72. He also has won two PGA titles and 
two U.S. Opens. 
</P>
<P>
Trevino will go down in my book as a great golfer, and one with a great sense 
of humor as well. 
</P>
<P>
GEORGE DODELEIN 
</P>
<P>
Canoga Park 
</P>
