<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEEKEND HIGHLIGHTS FOR L.A. INTERNATIONAL FILM FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL WILMINGTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The American Film Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival continues 
at the Cineplex Odeon Century Plaza Cinemas this weekend. Highlights from 
today's and Sunday's program follow. 
</P>
<P>
TODAY 
</P>
<P>
'My Uncle's Legacy' 
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia, 1988, 107 minutes 
</P>
<P>
 6:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Krsto Papic's scathing memory-film of life in a teacher's school in the 1950s, 
and of the symbiotic relationship between a rebellious young student and his 
uncle, a charismatic Party leader, gets high marks for political audacity and 
independence, medium ones on dramatic execution and psychological edge. Papic 
keeps building toward an explosion of outrage. But, since this isn't an 
American vigilante thriller the combustion never quite arrives. MICHAEL 
WILMINGTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Motion Picture Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
