<P>
'Krik? Krak! Tales of a Nightmare' 
</P>
<P>
Haiti/United States/Canada, 1988, 82 minutes 
</P>
<P>
 4:20 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 Haiti's Duvalier dictatorship survived as long as it did in part by exploiting 
the population's widespread regard for and fear of voodoo, which should make 
interesting documentary fodder. But this grim, elliptical compendium of 
recollections of unpleasantness among the peasants, directed by Jac Avila and 
Vanyoska Gee, is more often simply ominous and confusing. CHRIS WILLMAN 
